---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---
<BaseLayout title="Methodology — ITR Atlas">
  <article class="prose">
    <h1>Methodology</h1>

    <h2>What ITR measures</h2>
    <p>Information transfer rate (ITR) estimates how many bits per minute a user can communicate
       through an interface. For discrete selection it is usually computed with the
       <strong>Wolpaw formula</strong> for bits per selection:</p>
    <pre class="mono">B = log2(N) + P*log2(P) + (1-P)*log2((1-P)/(N-1))</pre>
    <p>multiplied by selections per minute. Here <em>N</em> is the number of targets and
       <em>P</em> is accuracy.</p>

    <h2>Why a single number is often misleading</h2>
    <p>The Wolpaw ITR is not a neutral measurement — it is the channel capacity of an
       <em>idealized</em> channel: one where every target is equally likely (a uniform prior), errors
       are spread evenly over the other targets (symmetric and memoryless), selection time is fixed,
       and no time is spent correcting mistakes. The formula above is <em>exactly</em> the capacity of
       that idealized channel. It is therefore a valid <strong>upper bound</strong> — but real
       interfaces violate every one of those assumptions, so it systematically over-states the rate
       actually achieved, and the gap grows with both accuracy and the number of symbols
       (<a href="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0078432">Speier, Arnold &amp; Pouratian 2013</a>;
       <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23448963/">Yuan et al. 2013</a>).</p>
    <p>More honest estimators relax the assumptions one at a time: a confusion-matrix mutual
       information drops the symmetric-error assumption
       (<a href="https://www.yumpu.com/en/document/view/33702582/statistical-modelling-issues-for-the-adaptive-brain-interface">Nykopp 2001</a>;
       <a href="https://archive-ouverte.unige.ch/unige:47811">Kronegg et al. 2005</a>); a language
       model drops the uniform-prior assumption (Speier and colleagues, above); and a continuous control channel
       needs a throughput model, not a discrete-selection count, in the first place. The rest of this
       page is, in effect, a tour of which assumption each entry breaks and what we use instead of the
       idealized number.</p>

    <h2>The predictor is part of the measurement</h2>
    <p>Information is uncertainty removed, so a bits figure is never a property of the channel
       alone — it depends on the <em>predictor</em> you assume on the receiving end. Redundancy that
       a good language model reconstructs for free never had to cross the channel, so a stronger
       predictor yields a lower, truer information rate. This means the predictor has to be held
       <strong>constant across every entry</strong>, or the comparison breaks. We use a conservative
       full-context bound of about <strong>1 bit per character</strong> for English text throughout.
       Shannon's prediction experiments first bracketed printed English between 0.6 and 1.3 bits/char
       (<a href="https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/6773263">Shannon 1951</a>); modern estimates
       land just above our working value — about <strong>1.12 bits/char</strong> by extrapolating
       neural language models to unlimited data
       (<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7512401/">Takahira et al. 2016</a>) and
       about <strong>1.22 bits/char</strong> in a large-scale replication of Shannon's guessing game
       (<a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7514546/">Ren et al. 2020</a>) — so 1
       bit/char is a deliberate, slightly conservative floor. The per-word figure is not a separate
       measurement: text-entry rates define one word as five characters
       (<a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/642611.642632">Soukoreff &amp; MacKenzie 2003</a>), the same
       convention behind every words-per-minute figure in this atlas, so the bound is equivalently
       <strong>5 bits per word</strong>.</p>
    <p>Speech is the clearest illustration of why this matters. A widely cited cross-language study
       reports an average information rate of <strong>~39 bits/second</strong> for spoken language
       (<a href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/sciadv.aaw2594">Coupé et al. 2019</a>). That
       study set out to compare encoding efficiency <em>across</em> 17 languages, and for that
       purpose it uses a syllable-level entropy estimated from local context — an estimator chosen to
       be computable and comparable across languages with very different corpus resources. It does
       its job well. But a local-context estimate counts redundancy that a full-context predictor
       would resolve, so it measures a different quantity than the channel-net information this atlas
       tracks. Adopting that ~39 bps here would hold speech to a more lenient predictor than the
       full-context Shannon bound we apply to QWERTY, Morse, and the BCI spellers — so the mismatch
       would be ours, not the study's.</p>
    <p>Hold the predictor fixed and the gap disappears. When conversational English is measured with
       a large language model as the predictor — the same full-context standard we apply to text — it
       lands at <strong>~13 bits/second</strong>
       (<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.08890">Bergey &amp; DeDeo 2024</a>), matching our text
       entries (≈150 wpm × 5 bits/word). Same words, same predictor, same rate: spoken word and
       written text carry essentially identical net information, because the information lives in the
       language, not the channel carrying it. The 3× spread is an estimator difference, not a
       modality one — which is why we keep one predictor across every entry.</p>

    <h2>What we rank on: realized output, not raw channel bits</h2>
    <p>Every entry is ranked on the information the interface <em>actually delivers to its
       application</em>, measured under one predictor held constant across the whole atlas. Two
       estimators cover every entry:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>The output is language</strong> → character-entropy throughput
         (characters/min × ~1 bit/char), the same full-context Shannon predictor used for QWERTY
         everywhere. This covers the keyboards, Morse, eye-typing, and the BCI spellers — P300, SSVEP,
         c-VEP — because all of them emit English text.</li>
      <li><strong>The channel is continuous cursor motion</strong> → Fitts throughput,
         <strong>log₂(A/W + 1)</strong> per movement divided by movement time, computed from the
         interface's own geometry. This covers the mouse, trackball, stylus, tongue drive, gaze
         pointing, and the cursor BCIs. Accuracy is folded in the way Fitts always handles it — via
         the <em>effective</em> width W<sub>e</sub> = 4.133·SD of the movement endpoints (ISO 9241-9),
         which discounts the information per movement to the precision actually achieved, so there is
         no separate error term and you cannot game it by moving fast and missing. Where a source
         publishes no endpoint scatter (e.g. the sensorimotor-rhythm cursor), we say so and fall back
         to a plain completion-rate discount.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Every raw-channel count — Wolpaw, log₂(N), achieved-bitrate, Webgrid BPS, c-VEP's discrimination
       rate — is the capacity of an idealized channel, so it is kept only as a secondary
       <strong>ceiling</strong>, never the ranked number. The reason log₂(N) cannot be the rank is that
       it scores the decoder's alphabet size, and that size is a knob. Neuralink's Webgrid carves a
       continuous cursor into 900 cells (~9.8 bits/selection) — make the grid denser and the number
       rises while the control is unchanged. EEG2Code makes the point unanswerable: it discriminates
       <strong>500,000</strong> random codes at ~100% from 2 s of EEG, log₂(500,000) ≈ 19 bits per
       selection, 701 bits/min — and the authors themselves flag a "ceiling effect" where those bits
       cannot be converted into control
       (<a href="https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0221909">Nagel &amp; Spüler 2019</a>). A speller
       that emits English but is credited log₂(40) per letter is being held to a more lenient predictor
       than QWERTY at 1 bit/char — the same apples-to-oranges mismatch we rejected for speech.</p>
    <p>This also dissolves a question that used to drive the framework: whether a given selection is
       "really" pointing. The decoder's mechanism — a cursor traversing space (Fitts), a frequency or
       code classifier (SSVEP, c-VEP), or covert attention with no movement at all (P300) — only
       determines <em>which ceiling label</em> an entry carries. It never touches the rank, so we do
       not have to adjudicate, for instance, whether covert attention obeys Fitts' law. As a sanity
       check on the Fitts side, the able-bodied ~10 BPS reported on Webgrid reduces by this method to
       ~4.1 bits/s, matching the independently-measured throughput of a physical mouse (~4.5 bits/s).</p>
    <p>One carve-out keeps the rule honest. When the output is <em>not</em> language — a
       command-and-control BCI choosing among N non-linguistic actions, say — log₂(N) over the real
       action prior <em>is</em> the realized measure, because there is no language predictor to apply.
       None of the current entries are that case; every speller here types English.</p>

    <h2>How we pick the reference number</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Use the original paper's own calculation when it exists and is sound.</li>
      <li>If the paper omits ITR, we compute one with a modality-appropriate method.</li>
      <li>If the paper's method is flawed, we recompute and show <strong>both</strong> derivations.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Provenance labels</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Author-reported · reproduced</strong> — we recomputed the number from the paper's stated inputs and matched it.</li>
      <li><strong>Author-reported · not reproduced</strong> — the paper gives a number but doesn't expose enough to recompute it.</li>
      <li><strong>Recomputed — paper omitted</strong> — no ITR in the paper; we computed one.</li>
      <li><strong>Recomputed — original flawed</strong> — the paper's method was broken; ours replaces it.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

